Just a couple of things which I have been pondering the last couple
days:

One of the first things I think we should do is get a 3-D display
engine running.  In doing this, we need to think about many issues
including:

- Are we going to write everything ourselves from the ground up, or
  should we build on one of the available 2-D graphics libraries such
  as jlib-1.5?  (I'm not aware of any freely available 3-D graphics
  engines -- maybe we should package ours up when it is done ... )

- Whatever we do, we need to make sure we can handle things like fog /
  visibility effects, and texture mapping.  It would be nice if
  whatever we do is portable, so flight-gear can run on multiple
  platforms.

- What approach are we going to use for hidden surface removal.  I
  assume we won't just be running on machines that can do this in
  hardware. :-)  My initial thoughts are that maybe we should
  implement some sort of z-buffering in software.  Another option
  would be to use some form of the painter's algorithm (draw furthest
  away things first) however, I think sorting by distance might have a 
  heavy performance penalty.

- We need to consider how our scenery/objects will be stored and
  organized.  This will probably influence how we design our 3-D
  engine.

So, do we have any 3-D graphics experts out there?  (If not, what are
we doing writing a flight simulator?)  :-) :-) :-)

Curt.
