I'm not sure that Flight Gear needs to have a whole new 3D engine, as
much as it needs to have a 3D API that can act as a thin layer over
whatever 3D engine is available on the target platform.  I strongly
believe that Flight Gear should be able to take advantage of such
technologies as OpenGL and Direct3D under Windows, and QuickDraw 3D on
the Mac, especially on machines that have 3D hardware.  (I don't know
what equivalent technologies exist under Unix, other than OpenGL.)

Of course, a baseline 3D engine should be written for those platforms
where a 3D engine is not readily available, but I think that can be
pursued as a separate project.

BTW, I guess I should introduce myself, I've just joined this mailing
list and am still getting up to speed on Flight Gear.  My name is
Robert Epps, and I am a disciple of the Evil Empire (a Windows
programmer).  My main area of interest is contributing to the 32-bit
Windows version of Flight Gear.  (I frankly believe that DOS and
16-bit Windows versions should not even be bothered with, because the
DOS market is well covered by FS5, and 16-bit Windows is just too
crippled for a highly graphical program like a flight simulator.)

