Subject: Scenery Design?
Sender: owner-flight-gear
Precedence: bulk
Reply-To: flight-gear@infoplane.com

I have a scenery design question for you all.

I was flying FS5 this weekend and made an observation.  The FS5 world
(obviously) is a flat plane with objects placed on top of it.  It
would be great if Flight-Gear's terrain could be a polygon (triangle)
mesh.  This would allow us to much more accurately represent the
world.

However, (and this is my observation) FS5's way of doing things is
much simpler, and requires much less processing time than would a 3-d
triangle mesh.

To do the things the way I would like, you would really have to spend
a huge effort doing hidden surface removal because conceivably, just
about any surface could at some time be in front of any other surface.

Two ways I can think of to do hidden surface removal on a DOS/Windows
PC is to sort all the polygons individually by distance from the
viewer, and then draw them from the furthest to the closest.  Sorting
becomes excruciatingly slow as the number of polygons increases.  A
triangle mesh would create lots of things to sort.  Another option
would be to use a software z-buffer.  This technique keeps track of
the depth (distance from viewer) of each pixel on the screen.  As you
are drawing each pixel of (scan converting) each line or polygon, you
check to see if that pixel is closer than the one that was already
drawn (using the z-buffer).  If it isn't closer, you draw the pixel,
and update the z-buffer, otherwise you just skip that pixel.  This way
you can draw the polygons in any order.

With FS5, though, things are much simpler.  I am speculating that for
each frame update, they sort all of their objects (usually not to
many) by distance from the viewer.  Then they draw out the ground
(easy -- just slap on the bitmaps) and finish by drawing all their
objects from furthest to closest.  This can still become slow if there
are many objects, but I can envision a few little tricks to speed
things up -- which they probably do.

So finally, the question is how do we want to approach this.  Do we
want to model our terrain using a triangle mesh?  This would pretty
much require a full fledged 3-d graphic engine, and would probably not
run to fast on machines without 3-d hardware support (i.e. high-end
SGI's)  Or, do we want to mimic FS5's simpler approach?  This would be
much easier to do on the programming side and would probably be able
to run much faster in general.  It would also make it easier if we
wanted to try to take advantage of all the wonderful scenery available
in bgl format?

I'd love to hear your thoughts,

Thanks,

Curt.
