Curt,

Just a couple of observations on this. The naval simulator Harpoon uses a
Lambert Conformal Conic projection for its surface representations. These
are based on Defense Mapping Agency Global Navigation Charts. The docs do
point out, however, that this is possible in large part because most naval
activity takes place in areas of the earth where little distortion is
created by the conical representation. Also, Harpoon does not have to deal
with the "look down" factor from FL 330 which exists in a flight simulator.
On a polar flight, for instance, these distortions would be unacceptable.

Certainly some government agencies, such as NASA, DMA amd others have
already discovered ways of properly representing topographical features and
structures on a simulated "globe". Obviously most of these have been
designed for use on a mainframe of supercomputer. It's possible though, that
some of the *principles* which they use could be downsized to the PC.

And what about MS's Space Simulator. I haven't seen it yet, but is it
possible that they have incorporated a better model for representing the
Earth into it?

Good luck. This will be one of the most important decisions and design tasks
that your team will face.

Shmuel


