> - Are we going to write everything ourselves from the ground up, or
>   should we build on one of the available 2-D graphics libraries such
>   as jlib-1.5?  (I'm not aware of any freely available 3-D graphics
>   engines -- maybe we should package ours up when it is done ... )

I haven't gotten a chance to look a jlib yet (Just got back from vacation)
so I haven't seen how well it would handle some of the concepts I have
floating in my head.  (Subbitmaps, etc.)  Too many graphics packages
assume that a bitmap will be a contiguous memory region.  That's often
not the case.

> - Whatever we do, we need to make sure we can handle things like fog /
>   visibility effects, and texture mapping.  It would be nice if
>   whatever we do is portable, so flight-gear can run on multiple
>   platforms.

I've been thinking of how to implement fog/visibility effects.  It seems
the best way is to modify palette entries (on 8 bit displays).  I think
this means that pallette allocation is going to have to change as conditions
change.  So whatever  library we use is going to have to allow us to
allocate and deallocate palette entries.  In the case of a full palette,
the allocation routine should give the closest match.  There should
also be some sort of palette priority. (i.e. I NEED this color, but that
one is just an added touch.)  Both clouds, fog, and haze can be simulated
by semitransparent polygons.  The polygon is assigned a red, green, and
blue transparency and luminance, and the colors of things behind are 
multiplied by these transparencies and the luminance is added.  You can
do some fairly realistic stuff like this.

Texture mapping is generally implemented over the polygon graphics.  The
polygon structure would contain a pointer to the texture bitmap.  Textures
are displayed by ray casting (similar to ray tracing).  For each pixel
the point of interection with the texture bitmap is calculated.  I think
it's best to get the polygons working before worrying about texture mapping.

> - What approach are we going to use for hidden surface removal.  I
>   assume we won't just be running on machines that can do this in
>   hardware. :-)  My initial thoughts are that maybe we should
>   implement some sort of z-buffering in software.  Another option
>   would be to use some form of the painter's algorithm (draw furthest
>   away things first) however, I think sorting by distance might have a 
>   heavy performance penalty.

I've played around with this a bit in the past, and rough distance sorting
seems to work best.  The quickest way of doing this seems to be defining
a midpoint normal for each polygon.  First you eliminate all polygons with
normals facing away from the viewer and those outsize the viewport, then you 
calculate distance to the midpoint of the remaining polygons and sort to get 
a z list of all the visible polygons.

> - We need to consider how our scenery/objects will be stored and
>   organized.  This will probably influence how we design our 3-D
>   engine.

I think a list like this would do the trick.....

typedef struct _FG_SCN_RECORD {
  FG_INT32  objtype;             /* code for type of object            */
  FG_INT32  length;              /* length of this record              */
  FG_INT32  lat0,lon0,lat1,lon1; /* lat/lon range where it is visibile */
/* object date goes here */
} FG_SCN_RECORD;

typedef struct _FG_3DPOLY_RECORD {
  FG_INT32  objtype;             /* set to FG_OBJ_3DPOLY               */
  FG_INT32  length;              /* set to length of this record       */
  FG_INT32  lat0,lon0,lat1,lon1; /* lat/lon range where it is visible  */
  FG_INT32  color;               /* color of this polygon (RGB)        */
  FG_I3VECT center;              /* polygon center                     */
  FG_I3VECT normal;              /* polygon normal                     */
  FG_INT32  n_vertices;          /* number of vertices                 */
/* vertex list goes here */
} FG_3DPOLY_RECORD;

#define FG_OBJ_GROUP 0
#define FG_OBJ_3DPOLY 1
...etc...

It's easily extended and allow for grouping of objects.  For example
a group of polygons might look like this.  It's also fairly easy to scan.
It's also easy to define a text scenery language for compilation.

objtype=0
length=length of this group
lat0,lon0,lat1,lon1=  limits for this group
  objtype=1
  length=length of this polygon
  lat0,lon0,lat1,lon1=  limits for this polygon
  color=255 (as blue as blue can be)
  center=               coordinates of polygon center
  normal=               vector normal
  n_vertices=3
  vertex1,vertex2,vertex3
 
  next polygon
end of group

