I agree.  It was my intention to somehow obatain a 1 nmi resolution
ground level map for the world and use that as a basis for the scenery
world. (It would be a semi rectangular mesh rather than triangular,
but you get the point.)  In interesting areas the mesh could be finer.
I was also thinking of determining ground polygon color by altitude
and season.  (Although it would be nice to get a similar resolution
map of the actual ground color.  Anyone have a digitized real-color
world map? Both summer and winter?)



> To do the things the way I would like, you would really have to spend
> a huge effort doing hidden surface removal because conceivably, just
> about any surface could at some time be in front of any other surface.

If each polygon has a visibility range and other selection criteria,
the number of calcuations to be done can be greatly reduced. (See my
last message about using the polygon normal to get rid of invisible polygons.)

(discussion of Z buffering deleted)

(discussion of Z sorting deleted)

In general, Z buffering in software works better if your number of
polygons to be displayed is 10% of the number of pixels.  I don't think
that'll be the case for our FS.  

Another method that hasn't been discussed is ray casting.  For each display
pixel you calculate the closest intercepted polygon.  I've never done it
for more than a subsection of a display, though. (i.e. texture mapping
a polygon.)

As far as using BGL and FS4 scenery, I'd like to see modules that allowed
it, but I don't think I'd like that to be our primary scenery method.

Eric
