Flight-Gear developers,

I was just looking at the code for a program called xearth-1.0.  It is
a neat little utility (for Unix/X11) that displays a shaded view of
the earth from any position, using either a mercator or orthographic
projection.  It even knows the current sun position, and can shade out
the dark portions of the earth.

They use a very simple little idea which allows them to render the
"globe" accurately, even if the view is directly over one of the
poles.  I will attempt to describe the algorithm without understanding
it 100%. :-) They run all the data points (outlines of continents,
etc.)  through a simple transformation before displaying them.  For
instance, you can just rotate all your coordinates by a constant value
so that your current lat,lon equals 0,0.  Then you can proceed to
display your surroundings with the assumption that lat = y, lon = x
(or whichever way it goes).  They do things just a bit diffent than
what I have described, but the ideas is basically the same.  The
mercator projection centered on a point other than on the equator
yields some interesting maps since the distortions aren't in the usual
places.

    (They store all their data points in (x,y,z) format, such that
    each point will fall on the unit circle.  They then scale their
    coordintate by 30000 and keep them as integers ... this probably
    saves some calculations some where along the way)

So, what do you think about doing something like this to modeling our
world?

Thanks,

Curt.
